Problems with Docker (Standalone)
Single‑host limitation: Containers run on one host; if the host fails, everything dies.

No auto‑healing: If a container crashes, Docker won’t restart it automatically.

No auto‑scaling: You can’t scale containers up/down based on load.

No built‑in load balancing: Docker bridge networking is basic; no service discovery or LB.

Limited enterprise features: No firewall, API gateway, or governance features out of the box.

✅ How Kubernetes Solves These
Clustered architecture: Multiple nodes managed together; workloads distributed automatically.

Auto‑healing: Pods are restarted if they fail; deployments ensure desired state.

Auto‑scaling: Horizontal Pod Autoscaler (HPA) scales pods based on CPU/memory/load.

Load balancing: kube‑proxy and Services provide stable IPs, DNS, and traffic distribution.

Enterprise support: Integrates with firewalls, API gateways, RBAC, and cloud providers.

🏗 Kubernetes Architecture
Control Plane
API Server: Entry point; exposes Kubernetes to external clients.

ETCD: Key/value store for cluster state.

Scheduler: Decides which node runs each pod.

Controller Manager: Ensures desired state (replicas, jobs, endpoints).

Cloud Controller Manager: Integrates with cloud providers (EKS, AKS, GKE).

Data Plane (Worker Nodes)
Kubelet: Ensures pods are running on the node.

Container Runtime: Runs containers (containerd, CRI‑O).

Kube‑proxy: Provides networking, IP allocation, and load balancing.

📦 Pods vs Containers
In Docker, the smallest unit is a container.

In Kubernetes, the smallest unit is a pod (which can wrap one or more containers).

📑 Deployments
Deployment: Abstraction for managing pods.

Creates a ReplicaSet → which ensures the desired number of pods.

Provides auto‑healing and auto‑scaling.

